Text.Value: I see. Your blessed mum was providing for her family, but the young tiefling is a thieving devil.
Ugh. Get your head outta my head!
Don't blame you for trying, but I gotta eat. Give me the amulet, I pay you fair, and we're square.
Not long, matter of fact.
And here's your reward. We're square now. Get lost.
Good to be back behind the walls, have to say. For as long as that lasts.
Bet he's learned his lesson now.
Wherever it came from, at least it's something to remember her by.
Got nothing to say to you. You got nothing I want.
Ain't the same and you know it.
You mean this locket? How much is it worth to you?
My mum gave me that locket on her godsdamned deathbed. The boy took the thing. I know it.
They didn't pay her much. They owed her a perk or two.
You're right - I'm joking.
Tell me you are, and this doesn't have to end in blood.
OH, BUT IT DOES!
Blood? Sounds like a happy ending to me.
Let me guess - it wasn't your mother's to give you in the first place, was it?
Kind of you to offer, but that boy ain't giving it up, not even to one of his own. I'm sure of it.
Not in the mood to talk right now. It ain't you, so leave it.
I think you can up your offer a little. It was a gift from your mother, after all.
And here's your reward. We're square now. Get lost.
Then I guess we're going to have problems. Because I'm keeping it.
*I took my leave.*
Finally.
Kind of you to offer, but that boy ain't giving it up. I'm sure of it.
Attack him.
Yeah, thanks to you.
Quit whining, and give me the locket. It'll save me the effort of picking your pocket later.
It's the last thing of mum's I have... it's worth everything to me.
Hey. Thanks for stepping between me and the kid.
And it looks like someone took my money too. Got nothing to give you but my thanks.

EditorData.AnimationTags: Barth searches pockets for gold DUPE -RS

Text.Value: It's gonna be hard to wear a necklace when you ain't got a neck. Give it back.
W-what? Get your head outta my head!
Anyway, I should go. See you around.
Read his mind.
Yeah. I know she would.
You're all right by me.
Well, at least you can have it back now.
That's it. That is bloody it.
Thanks to you, I almost lost my locket. My mum gave that to me on her deathbed.
Finally.
Watch your bags, huh? Learn from my mistakes.

EditorData.logicalname: Not Knocked Out | Not Angry | Met

Text.Value: I'll say this for those devils: they know how to throw a punch.

EditorData.logicalname: Knocked Out | Not Angry | Not Met

Text.Value: What're you waiting for? I told you I'd give you some coin. Hand it over!
If that ain't enough, too bad. It's all I got.
The nerve of that smirking little rat.

EditorData.logicalname: Not Knocked Out | Not Angry | Not Met

Text.Value: I appreciate the kindness friend, but I ain't getting the locket back. Not now.
That kid stole the one thing that means anything to me.

RuleGroup.RuleString: CLERIC_EVIL or FIGHTER or MONK or PALADIN_EVIL

Text.Value: If you don't want another beating, give me the locket. Now.
On second thoughts, I'm keeping it.
Nothing. I'm sad, is all. Leave it alone.
Speaking of the locket... can I have it?
You'd best be joking.
Now hand it over, or we're gonna have problems, you and me.
My mum gave me that amulet. But I think she'd be happy knowing the kid has it now.
Come on, spit it out. What aren't you telling me about the locket?
Hand it over to him.
Got a beating, thanks to you. But at least I got my locket back.

EditorData.logicalname: Knocked Out | Angry | Not Met | Has Locket

Text.Value: Someone stole the damn amulet off me again. Don't want to talk about it.
Thanks to you, that kid has my locket. My mum gave that to me on her deathbed.
And it looks like someone took my money too. Got nothing to give you but my thanks.
Thanks to you, that kid has my mum's locket and I got a beating.

EditorData.logicalname: Knocked Out | Angry | Not Met | No Locket

Text.Value: She stole it from a house she cleaned, all right?
Locket. Now.
Leave.
Let me get this straight - you're annoyed that somebody stole your stolen property?
You're all right by me, friend.
I... I don't know what to say.
Yeah, all right, it wasn't.
Anyway, I meant what I said. Thanks for what you did. I gotta go.
Thank you kindly.
Not much of an heirloom then... unless there's a tale behind it, maybe?
Should've seen that, but my temper was up.
Here's the locket. It's all yours.
Forget the coin. The locket's yours. Take it.
And if you twist the pup's arm, he'll yelp, and the wolves'll come running.
Can't believe the kid thought he could snatch my mum's locket and get away with it.
Fine. I'll give you everything I've got and you can choke on it for all I care. Give me the amulet.
Was in another family right up 'til mum stole it. But it's mine now - all I have.

EditorData.AnimationTags: Barth's mother lifts locket from drawer- stuffs into apron -RS

Text.Value: I know it's stupid. It's all I have of her, is all.
Read his mind.
Heirloom, is it? Been in your family long?
I'll see about getting it back into your hands.
Thought so.
Hand it over to him.
You found it? I... I don't know what to say.
How did you... all right, fine. I'll give you some coin for it.
On second thought, I quite like this bauble. Think I'll keep it for myself.
Never said she was an angel, did I? But she sure as hells didn't have horns on her head!
Kind of you, friend. Here's something for your troubles.
'Some coin'? Try 'lots of coin' - or else the trinket stays with me.
I'll say this for you devils: you know how to throw a punch.
Get out of my face. Got nothing to say to you.
Get out of my face. Got nothing to say to you.

Synopsis: Non-critpath. Takes place after the player resolves the confronation between this adventurer and the thiefling boy who stole the adventurer's necklace.
